We are going to use a different image this time: a 2D scan of two maize blades. Make sure you place IMAG0001_rz.JPG in the raw folder.

Now let's use Image to load the image. But this time, we are going to convert it to grayscale with the .convert('L') option instead of .convert('RGB').

Sidenote: You probably noticed last assigment that we kept writting over and over again parameters cmap = 'Greys_r', vmin=0, vmax=255. If you are going to use the same set of parameters over and over again, you can declare them in a dictionary, and the pass that dictionary of keyword arguments (kwargs) with **. That's what **kwargs mean in several documentation pages: additional parameters that can be passed.

In [2]:
imkw = {'cmap':'Greys_r', 'vmin':0, 'vmax':255}
src = '..' + os.sep + 'raw' + os.sep
filename = 'IMAG0001_rz.JPG'

with open(src + filename, "rb") as imagefile:
    picture = Image.open(imagefile)
    picture.load()
gray = np.asarray(picture.convert('L')) # convert to grayscale instead of RGB, so our image will be single-channel from the get-go

# What happens if you comment out the line below?

You probably noticed two things between the histogram and the image itself:

  • There is a large gap between foreground and background pixel intensities, which means there is a high chance Otsu is a good choice.
  • The foreground (the blades) actually are much darker than the background, which is lighter.

It is convenient to stick to the convention that background is dark (0-valued) and foreground is light. We can easily invert the intensities by doing gray.max() - gray.

In [5]:
# inverting colors

img = gray.max() - gray
plt.imshow(img, **imkw);
  • We then compute Otsu for img and have binary be the binarized image
  • And plot binary. Remember that for binarized images, the max value is True or 1, so we don't need imkw in this case.
In [6]:
thr = filters.threshold_otsu(img)
binary = img > thr
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1, figsize=(15,20), sharex=True, sharey=True)
ax.imshow(binary);

Part 2: Morphological Operations¶

We notice that Otsu did a good job as expected from the histogram. However, it is not perfect. Can you notice some problems? You might need to make the image vertical (again with .T) so the plot is even larger.

Some issues:

  • The text of the labels is still there
  • Near the tip of one of the blades, there are some stray background pixels that were wrongly labeled as foreground.
  • Part of midvein in one of the blades was wrongly labeled as background and deleted.
  • Part of the margin was also wrongly labeled as foreground.

Fortunately, we can solve most of these issues with a combination of the two main morphological operations: dilation and erosion. The key insight is that stray pixels and stray holes are very small compared to the main objects of interest (the blades), which are large.

2.1 Our first erosion¶

Let's go back to our maize image. Let's remove the pixels corresponding to the label by first eroding the image. Ideally, after the erosion these stray pixels should be gone, so when we dilate, they don't grow back.

In [10]:
# Make sure you understand the code and its parameters
# Add labels

its = 1
erode = ndimage.binary_erosion(binary, iterations=its)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(2,1, figsize=(15,7), sharex=True, sharey=True)
ax[0].imshow(binary);
ax[1].imshow(erode);
fig.tight_layout();

Maybe eroding one time was not enough: you can still see hints of the label. The stray pixels near one of the blade tips are gone, though. Increase its until you are satisfied. What happens if you use large iterations numbers?

2.2 Our first dilation (and opening)¶

Now let's recover the original blade shapes by dilating by the same number of iterations. This erosion+dilation combination is also our first opening.

In [11]:
# Make sure you understand the code and its parameters
# Add labels

dilate = ndimage.binary_dilation(erode, iterations=its)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(3,1, figsize=(15,11), sharex=True, sharey=True)
ax[0].imshow(binary);
ax[1].imshow(erode);
ax[2].imshow(dilate)
fig.tight_layout();

The dilated (opened) image should look like the initial, binarized one minus the label, border, and other stray pixels. If they are still showing up, you need to increase the iterations for the erosion (and also increase the iterations for the following dilation.)

2.3 Our second dilation¶

Now let's dilate again, this time, to fix the "holes" in one of the blades.

In [12]:
# Add labels

its = 1
dilate2 = ndimage.binary_dilation(dilate, iterations=its)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(2,1, figsize=(15,7), sharex=True, sharey=True)
ax[0].imshow(dilate);
ax[1].imshow(dilate2);
fig.tight_layout();

If after dilating you still notice the holes, then you need to increase the iterations. What happens if you dilate too much?

2.4 Our second erosion (closing)¶

Let's erode (by the same number of iterations used in the second dilation), so that the blades go back to their original size.

In [13]:
# Add labels
erode2 = ndimage.binary_erosion(dilate2, iterations=its)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(3,1, figsize=(15,11), sharex=True, sharey=True)
ax[0].imshow(dilate);
ax[1].imshow(dilate2);
ax[2].imshow(erode2)
fig.tight_layout();

For the final image, we should have closed all the small holes. Compare the final image with our initial binary.

Notice that the slices oss only guarantee that the connected component will be contained. It does not prevent other connected componets to crash into the party. Let's fix that.

# Make sure you understand the code

blades = [None for i in range(len(oss))]
for i in range(len(blades)):
    box = erode2[oss[i]].copy()
    box[label[oss[i]] != i+1] = 0
    box = np.pad(box, 25)
    blades[i] = box

fig, ax = plt.subplots(len(oss),1, figsize=(15,5), sharex=False, sharey=False)

Part 4: Getting borders¶

But what if we want the perimeter of each blade? We need to convolve by

$$\begin{bmatrix} -1 & -1 & -1 \\ -1 & +8 & -1 \\ -1 & -1 & -1 \end{bmatrix}.$$

Notice that if we are centered on an exterior pixel (background), we get $$-1*0-1*0-1*0-1*0+8*0-1*0-1*0-1*0-1*0 = 0.$$

If we are centered on an interior pixel (foreground), we also get: $$-1*1-1*1-1*1-1*1+8*1-1*1-1*1-1*1-1*1 = 0.$$

The only way we get something other than 0, is if we are on the border of the blade or right next to the border. Read carefully the following code and make sure you understand what's going on.

In [18]:
border_kernel = np.array([
    [-1,-1,-1],
    [-1,8,-1],
    [-1,-1,-1]
])
border = ndimage.convolve(blades[0].astype(int), border_kernel)
border[border < 0] = 0
border[border > 0] = 1
border = border.astype(bool)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1, figsize=(15,7), sharex=True, sharey=True)
ax.imshow(border);
fig.tight_layout();
